# ADR-0003 — Execution Strategy

Status: Proposed

---

# Context

The Planner decides WHAT should happen.

The Workflow executes HOW it happens.

A missing layer still exists:

Should the Plan be executed immediately?

Should it wait for approval?

Should it stop after one step?

Should it execute sequentially?

Should it execute in parallel?

These are execution policies.

They should not belong to Planner.

They should not belong to Workflow.

---

# Decision

Introduce an Execution Strategy abstraction.

Responsibilities

Planner

↓

creates Plan

Execution Strategy

↓

decides how the Plan should be executed

Workflow

↓

executes according to the Strategy

Runtime

↓

executes one Employee

---

# Responsibilities

Planner

- Analyze Goal
- Produce Plan
- Never execute

Execution Strategy

- Decide execution policy
- Select next step
- Pause when required
- Resume when possible

Workflow

- Execute Plan
- Update step state
- Retry
- Track progress

Runtime

- Execute one Employee
- Handle Tool Calls
- Return Result

---

# Initial MVP

Only one strategy exists.

ImmediateExecutionStrategy

Behavior

Receive Plan

↓

Execute every step sequentially

↓

Finish

No approval

No retry

No branching

No priorities

No deadlines

---

# Strategy Interface

abstract class ExecutionStrategy {

    ExecutionDecision decide(Plan plan);

}

ExecutionDecision contains:

- execution mode
- selected steps

Nothing else.

---

# Why

Planning

Execution Policy

Execution

are three different responsibilities.

Keeping them independent allows:

- Human approval
- Dry run
- Simulation
- Parallel execution
- Resume
- Scheduling

without changing Planner or Runtime.

---

# Future Strategies

ImmediateExecutionStrategy

ApprovalExecutionStrategy

ParallelExecutionStrategy

